<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 3 日星期四 11:12:20 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Israeli Reservists Start Missing Duty, Threatening Military Unity and Readiness]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>拒绝任职是改革司法机构的努力如何导致国家分裂的最明显例子之一<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106909"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828271?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列空军学员在毕业典礼上。飞行训练因教官抗议而中断。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ariel Schalit/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106909"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 6:50 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-threatening-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——上校尼西姆·约格夫 (Nissim Yogev) 在以色列空军担任战斗飞行领航员 25 年，参加了以色列与黎巴嫩的战争，亲眼目睹他最好的朋友在战斗中失踪，再也没有回来。上周，他说他做出了一生中最艰难的决定，当时他泪流满面地写信给他的指挥官，表示他将停止报到志愿预备役，他在空军唯一的飞行学校训练学员。</p><p> “没有我，飞行学校可能会过得很好，但只要事情继续这样下去，我就不能接受自己，”他写道。</p><p> 64岁的约格夫上周缺席了第一天的教学，当时他正在执行数千名像他一样的志愿预备役军人的威胁，在以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的联盟<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通过了限制权力努力的第一部分</a>后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，他将暂停服役。</a>最高法院。预备役军人表示，这项立法破坏了以色列的自由民主，破坏了他们冒着生命危险的社会契约。组织推动拒绝服役的最大团体之一的“兄弟连”表示，已经有数千人像约格夫一样拒绝服预备役。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="640" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828288?width=639&amp;height=640" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">戴墨镜的尼西姆·约格夫上校和一位 1986 年在行动中失踪的朋友。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：尼西姆·约格夫</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>目前还不清楚有多少像尤格夫这样的预备役军人已经错过了他们应该服役的日子。但有迹象表明，军方已经感受到了损失。一位知情人士称，在最近的至少一期飞行员培训课程中，几乎没有教员到场值班。这个问题变得如此尖锐，以至于飞行训练学校的负责人上周致函学员家长，表示训练仍在继续，尽管许多教官尚未出现。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡表示，预备役抗议是不民主的。士兵们试图向政府发号施令。他的联盟中的一些人称这是一次未遂的军事政变。该联盟表示，它正在制定受到选民青睐的政策，选民称最高法院由自由派法官控制，他们太快推翻了人民的意愿。他们说，这项立法旨在恢复政府不同部门之间的适当权力平衡。</p><p>预备役军人的抗议是内塔尼亚胡推动司法机构改革如何导致国家分裂的最明显例子之一。以色列军队长期以来一直是分裂社会的团结力量，对于这个自 75 年前建国以来一直深陷冲突的国家至关重要。团结的削弱可能会损害以色列军队赖以生存的人民军队模式，而这种模式近年来已经<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-israel-army-service-is-required-for-all-that-could-now-change-2c76624d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">面临压力</a>。如果预备役人员的技能过时，它还可能以更直接的方式损害军队，影响作战准备。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828273?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尽管遭到大规模抗议，以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡仍继续推进司法改革。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·科恩/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>以色列国防部长约阿夫·加兰特在本周的议会委员会会议上表示：“对健康的损害是有限的，但从长远来看，有可能对健康造成损害。”</p><p>同样在本周，以色列军事参谋长与每一位上校及以上级别的军官举行了小组会议，讨论如何处理军队内部的政治分歧，因为这些师已经渗透到正规队伍中。</p><p>根据一名高级军官 2022 年 5 月的声明，以色列军队有数十万预备役军人，其中约有 12 万名现役预备役军人，年龄在 22 岁至 45 岁之间。超过现役预备役年龄的人可以继续服役志愿者担任预备役，有些人（例如约格夫）担任需要每周或每两周服务的职位，并提前安排值班日期。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>空军飞行教官的抗议将对以色列的司法改革产生什么影响？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>像尤格夫这样的飞行学院教练会提前几个月报名参加教学，并且预计会在需要时在短时间内赶到。他说他错过了七月底的第一天教学，并且不会出现在八月中旬的下一个预定教学日。</p><p> 47 岁的埃亚勒·纳维 (Eyal Naveh) 是以色列最精锐的突击队 Sayeret Matkal 的预备役军官，也是兄弟连抗议组织的领导人。他们不会上班的人。纳维说，他们包括情报和网络专家，以及海军预备役司令部的成员。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828279?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列预备役军人在特拉维夫的抗议活动中签署拒绝服役的声明。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Eyal Warshavsky/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>最令军方担忧的是数百名暂停服役的空军预备役军人。预备役抗议领导人表示，其中包括数百名现役战斗机飞行员、无人机操作员、导航员和教员。与大多数预备役军人不同，空军志愿者定期服役，是空军的支柱，而空军本身就是国家安全的支柱。</p><p>纳维表示，空军总部的许多退伍军人预备役人员已暂停服役，但他无法提供具体数字。他们有时会被要求就常规行动提供建议，并且在战时对军队至关重要。</p><p>当被问及数百名空军预备役人员拒绝服役时，以色列军方表示：“预备役飞行员是空军实现其目标的作战能力的基石，他们对以色列的安全做出了重大贡献。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-threatening-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“目前，空军完全有能力并做好了作战准备。长时间不报告可能会使[以色列国防军]和空军处于能力下降和战备状态下降的状态。”</p><p>当被问及有多少预备役军人暂停服役时，以色列军方拒绝发表评论。</p><p>暂停服役的教官表示，随着时间的推移，缺勤将影响以色列空军学员的训练计划。他们说，大多数教官都是拥有数十年经验的预备役军人，而且没有明确的替代者。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="1136" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828322?width=639&amp;height=1136" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">双桅船。奥弗·拉皮多特将军穿着一件 T 恤，上面写着：“独裁？决不。”</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Offer Lapidot</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>双桅船。 73 岁的空军学院前指挥官奥弗·拉皮多特将军表示，如果没有预备役军人的大力帮助，就没有足够的正规军教官为所有学员提供服务。</p><p>拉皮多特在空军度过了整个成年生活，主要担任战斗机飞行员和指挥官，直到最近担任教官，在内塔尼亚胡政府通过第一项司法立法的一周半前，他向指挥官发出了停职信。他表示希望施加足够的压力来阻止该法案通过。</p><p>他说，他被迫权衡“国家的安全，与我们为之奋斗并准备献出生命的国家的存在”。</p><p> 46 岁的祖尔·阿隆 (Zur Allon) 是一名科技公司首席执行官，也是炮兵特种部队的常备役军人，他已暂停服役，不过自两周前开始就没有要求他去上班。他表示，如果国家发生紧急情况，他将到岗。但他担心长时间的停顿可能会影响军队的战斗准备。</p><p> “它就像一辆汽车：把它放在车库里一年就不能用了，”他说。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 10:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-throne-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-throne-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>空军</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>空军</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Latest Problem: People Don’t Want to Go There]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着地缘政治紧张局势加剧，前往世界第二大经济体的游客减少，东西方鸿沟扩大<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827041?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近日，上海机场人烟稀少，旅行社组织的境外旅游来华的人数大幅减少。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：劳尔·阿里亚诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">范文欣</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-xi-jinping-reversed-his-zero-covid-policy-in-china-11672853171?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取消Covid-19限制</a>并重新开放边境半年后，几乎没有国际游客前来——这是中国与西方脱钩的另一个迹象，可能会产生长期负面影响。</p><p>外国游客的缺席在北京和上海等主要城市尤其明显，上半年到访这些城市的外国人人数总计不到 2019 年新冠疫情大流行前可比数字的四分之一。</p><p>在全国范围内，第一季度，只有 52,000 人次通过旅行社组织的旅行到达中国大陆，这是有全国数据的最新时期，而 2019 年第一季度有 370 万人次。与往年一样，近一半的游客来自自治岛屿台湾以及中国香港和澳门，而不是美国或欧洲等更远的地方。</p><p> “来自欧洲、美洲、日本和韩国的游客数量都在大幅下降，”半官方的中国旅游协会理事肖千惠在五月份的一次讲话中表示。</p><p>专家表示，海外游客和商人的减少意味着外国人亲眼看到中国并与当地人互动的机会减少，而这是缓解地缘政治紧张局势的一个重要因素。</p><p>游客稀缺也可能导致对华投资减少。研究公司荣鼎集团 (Rhodium Group) 的马克·维茨克 (Mark Witzke) 对政府数据进行的分析显示，第一季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">流入该国的外国直接投资降至</a>200 亿美元，而去年第一季度为 1000 亿美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019 年，新冠疫情爆发之前，南京的一座陵墓挤满了游客。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：苏洋/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>外国投资和入境人数下降之际，中国经济停滞不前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">房地产市场低迷</a>，青年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">失业率</a>创历史新高，人们越来越担心中国可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">陷入通货紧缩。</a>与今年前三个月相比，第二季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">中国经济几乎没有增长</a>。</p><p>抵达中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8" target="_blank" class="icon none">的航班数量不足</a>是造成抵达人数低的部分原因，航空公司尚未恢复到新冠疫情爆发前提供的服务水平。但中国和海外旅游专家表示，由于中国与西方关系恶化，外国游客也不愿前往，这让他们对访问更加谨慎。</p><p> 6月，美国政府发布旅行建议，警告美国人重新考虑前往中国大陆的旅行，因为所谓的“任意执行当地法律”，包括出境禁令和错误拘留的可能性。</p><p>波士顿商业顾问马特·凯利 (Matt Kelly) 表示，他对 15 年前骑自行车环游中国南方一座风景如画的山城桂林的旅行留下了美好的回忆。他又两次访问中国，但表示今天没有兴趣回去。</p><p> “我会回到我所熟悉的中国吗？是的！”他说。但现在，“中国似乎确实将自己描绘成非常反西方、反美国的人。这让我非常不安。”</p><p>位于宾夕法尼亚州的友好星球旅游公司（Friendly Planet Travel）是一家精品经营商，过去每年向中国派遣多达 1,500 名游客。其创始人兼总裁佩吉·戈德曼 (Peggy Goldman) 表示，自新冠疫情爆发以来，该公司还没有收到过任何要求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828850?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">马特·凯利，2008 年在中国桂林。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马特·凯利</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当她的团队研究人们在网上搜索的目的地时，“中国确实处于追踪的底部，”她说。 “围绕中国这个话题存在很多敌意。”</p><p>尽管高盛表示她相信中国最终会再次流行，但该公司尚未将其中国包裹重新上线。</p><p>总部位于奥斯汀的旅游科技公司 Mondee Holdings 的数据显示，2023 年上半年从北美到中国的休闲旅游约为 2019 年同期的 40%。 2019年，Mondee通过旅行社和其他中介机构销售了约50万个从北美飞往中国的航班，约占当年从北美飞往中国的所有航空旅行的五分之一。</p><p>哈里斯·布里肯律师事务所驻西雅图合伙人丹·哈里斯表示，尽管企业高管仍在询问前往中国的旅行，但许多人现在关注的是风险，而过去，他们想知道如何加快签证速度。为在中国的投资提供建议。</p><p> “公司非常非常关心他们的员工去中国。为什么他们不会呢？他提到了中国最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreign-firms-in-china-squeezed-by-u-s-disclosure-demands-beijings-security-clampdown-658ef8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对西方尽职调查公司和其他公司进行调查</a>的消息，其中包括政府对贝恩公司等全球咨询公司进行突击搜查。“除非迫不得已，否则人们不会去中国。”</p><p>哈里斯过去经常去中国北京工作，并在青岛停留购买啤酒和海鲜，他表示，他已告诉一些高管，他们的风险很低。但近年来，在公开批评中国政府后，他本人不再前往。</p><p>中国文化和旅游部没有回应置评请求。</p><p>中国官员最近与美国、欧洲和日本的商业协会举行了会议<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，向他们保证</a>中国仍然欢迎外国投资。</p><p>中国驻美国大使谢锋7月份在阿斯彭安全论坛上表示，两国游客应该互相访问。他建议举办旅游论坛并增加航班数量，并呼吁华盛顿调整其旅行建议。</p><p>外国游客的缺席不会像泰国或冰岛那样对中国造成伤害，因为这些国家的经济严重依赖游客。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-travelers-swarm-domestic-tourist-sites-a-positive-sign-for-economy-f45c4977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">目前，中国游客在国内旅游上的支出比 2019 年更多</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827025?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019年以来，张家界国家公园的游客量大幅下降。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：吴永兵/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>尽管如此，中国仍有许多企业依赖游客。缺乏它们意味着中国失去了向外国人展示更积极形象的机会。</p><p>中国中部的张家界国家公园是电影《阿凡达》中“浮山”的拍摄地，这里有令人惊叹的岩层，截至 5 月中旬，海外游客仅有 25,600 人次，而 2019 年前 5 个月的海外游客人数为 500,000 人次。</p><p>上海导游于雪（Snow Yu）过去带外国人参观的生意很红火，包括在 2017 年为金州勇士队和佐治亚理工学院黄夹克篮球队的高管担任导游。在疫情期间，边境基本关闭，他找了一份英语辅导的临时工作。</p><p>于已经回到了原来的工作岗位，主要带领当地的旅游团。但他们不需要他的英语能力，给的小费也较少。因此，他说他的收入比大流行前减少了近一半。</p><p> “世界需要互联，”他说，并补充说来自邻国的英语游客开始回来。</p><p>来自西方和东亚部分地区游客的下降已被俄罗斯游客数量的增加部分抵消，不过中国旅游专家表示，他们的消费有所减少。</p><p>今年6月，张家界国家公园邀请80多家国际旅行社进驻，其中大部分来自俄罗斯。当地官员承诺增加更多从中国北方邻国起飞的航班，或延长从中国其他城市起飞的现有航班。</p><p>旅游官员肖在讲话中呼吁中央政府提供更多支持。他强调，入境旅游可以“以类似于‘乒乓外交’的方式”帮助化解地缘政治紧张局势，他指的是20世纪70年代乒乓球运动员的交流，帮助中美关系解冻。</p><p>他引用了埃隆·马斯克母亲最近访问中国的例子，她在 Instagram 上发布了关于她的经历的积极信息。</p><p>另一个避开中国的群体是外籍人士，他们在前几年充当了中国社会与各自祖国之间的桥梁。许多人邀请家人和朋友来参观。</p><p> 37岁的投资顾问亚历山大·西拉科夫(Alexander Sirakov)去年8月从上海搬回祖国保加利亚。他说，他的外籍朋友圈子里的大多数人也都离开了，包括住在他大院里的 10 个外籍家庭中的 8 个。</p><p> “人们现在认为中国非常遥远，而且有些疏远，”他说。 “四年前正好相反，当时的中国非常开放、充满活力，是一个必去的地方。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——齐丽艳对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给范文欣： <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What Are North Korea’s Nuclear-Weapon Capabilities and Is the Threat Expanding?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>金正恩发誓永远不会交出核武器，这些武器有可能袭击美国任何地方<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11923952469699264706904587222722544736282"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
        "><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5CF434C5-8D62-429D-BAB3-0599A261F2F3&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fnorth-korea-nuclear-weapons-missiles-explained-11610712018&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">中国和俄罗斯代表团周四参加了平壤举行的阅兵式，这是自Covid-19大流行开始以来首次对朝鲜进行外国访问。 《华尔街日报》的 Dasl Yoon 解释了这三个国家之间不断发展的关系。照片：STR/AFP/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11923952469699264706904587222722544736282"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/timothy-w-martin" itemprop="url" rel="author">蒂莫西·W·马丁</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 4:19（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-nuclear-weapons-missiles-explained-11610712018"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>朝鲜认为其核计划对于政权生存至关重要，有助于阻止美国领导的入侵。数十年的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-north-koreas-kim-end-nuclear-summit-early-11551334804?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">无核化谈判</a>、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covert-chinese-trade-with-north-korea-moves-into-the-open-11607345372?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">经济制裁</a>和外交并没有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-koreas-kim-jong-un-says-u-s-is-biggest-enemy-11610154003?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">减缓平壤自行</a>宣布成为核国家的进程。</p><p>近年来，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">金正恩</a>政权的武器试验一直在以历史性的速度进行。仅2023年，朝鲜就<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-launches-suspected-long-range-missile-4fcd270f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">至少发射了四次</a>洲际弹道导弹，其射程可达美国本土。平壤公然发展武器计划，无视制裁并违背停止核生产的承诺。 2003年，它<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB112287647015701267?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">退出了《核不扩散条约》</a> ，这是阻止核武器扩散的主要全球承诺。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>军备竞赛</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB11923952469699264706904587222620375548562?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">金正恩罕见地一睹朝鲜的武器计划</a></li></ul></div></div><h3>朝鲜拥有什么核武器？</h3><p>美国陆军于 2020 年 7 月表示，朝鲜现在可能拥有 20 至 60 枚核弹，并且有能力每年制造 6 枚核弹。根据提供给美国的<a href="https://armedservices.house.gov/sites/republicans.armedservices.house.gov/files/03.29.23%20Milley%20Statement.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">书面证词</a>，2023 年 5 月，参谋长联席会议主席陆军上将马克·米利表示，朝鲜的武器测试和开发“对我们的祖国以及印太地区的盟友和伙伴构成了真正的威胁”立法者。</p><p>平壤尚未证明其能够可靠地用核武器打击美国。这需要开发一种能够承受重新进入大气层的巨大压力和热量的弹头。在测试中，朝鲜以陡峭的角度发射了洲际弹道导弹，部分原因是为了防止它们在美国领海溅落，这让人怀疑该技术是否可以以其平坦的弹道进行实际飞行。它还需要开发和测试可靠的瞄准系统。</p><p>金氏政权的许多短程武器也被认为具有核能力。</p><p>朝鲜已进行六次核试验。据韩国议员称，最近一次是在 2017 年 9 月，产量估计高达 100 吨，大约是 1945 年美国在日本长崎投下的原子弹的五倍。该国五年战略武器政策的目标是发展在一枚导弹上搭载多枚核弹头的能力。</p><p>美国和韩国官员表示，朝鲜已完成<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-appears-to-have-conducted-nuclear-test-1504411685?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">近六年来</a>首次核试验的准备工作。</p><h3>什么是洲际弹道导弹？</h3><p>洲际弹道导弹（洲际弹道导弹的缩写）已经存在了几十年，并在冷战期间获得了重要地位。它们设计用于从一个大陆旅行到另一个大陆，通常最小航程约为 3,400 英里或约 5,500 公里。但一些洲际弹道导弹的飞行距离可以超过 10,000 英里，从而允许更迂回的路线。只有美国、俄罗斯和中国等少数国家拥有陆基洲际弹道导弹，还有更多国家能够从潜艇发射此类导弹。</p><p>这种大型导弹的飞行速度可达每小时 15,000 英里。洲际弹道导弹采用亚轨道路径，离开地球大气层，然后降落在目标上。洲际弹道导弹可以携带核弹头以及其他类型的武器。</p><h3>朝鲜的导弹能打到美国本土吗？</h3><p>根据负责监管驻韩美军约 28,500 名驻韩美军的评估，2017 年 11 月发射的火星 15 导弹可能会袭击美国任何地方。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"></figure></div><p>导弹专家估计其射程为 8,100 英里，并表示朝鲜洲际弹道导弹发射后不到 30 分钟即可击中美国本土。平壤距美国西海岸5000多英里。</p><p> 2021 年 1 月， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-offers-a-rare-sneak-peek-at-north-koreas-weapons-program-11610712009" target="_blank" class="icon none">金提出了将飞行范围扩大到约 9,300 英里的目标</a>。韩国军方告诉立法者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-shoots-off-another-unknown-projectile-11648102443" target="_blank" class="icon none">，2022 年 3 月进行的全射程洲际弹道导弹测试</a>——这是四年多来的首次测试——显示了潜在的射程。</p><p>朝鲜在 2023 年 4 月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-fires-ballistic-missile-toward-japan-2c728f14https:/www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-fires-ballistic-missile-toward-japan-2c728f14" target="_blank" class="icon none">再次实现飞跃</a>，展示了新型 Hwasong-18 洲际弹道导弹，该导弹使用固体燃料而非液体燃料发动机，这一转变使其机动性更强，部署速度往往更快。三个月后，朝鲜再次试射火星 18 型导弹，并在空中飞行了约 74 分钟，这是迄今为止其弹道导弹发射的最长飞行时间。</p><p>该国的短程武器一再表明朝鲜有足够的能力打击韩国和日本——这两个国家都有美国海外军事基地。 2022 年 10 月 4 日，金氏政权<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-tests-worlds-resolve-by-sending-missile-over-japan-11664890236" target="_blank" class="icon none">在日本上空发射了一枚中程导弹</a>，该导弹沿高空轨迹飞行了约 2,800 英里。例如，美国在关岛的军事基地距离朝鲜大约 2,000 英里。</p><h3>朝鲜拥有什么类型的导弹？</h3><p>朝鲜拥有多种弹道导弹。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-koreas-kim-jong-un-says-u-s-is-biggest-enemy-11610154003" target="_blank" class="icon none">2021年初</a>，金正恩概述了该国的首要战略武器优先事项，包括核动力潜艇、高超音速导弹、更强大的洲际弹道导弹和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-kim-jong-un-wants-the-world-to-see-new-icbm-tests-as-satellite-technology-11647268293" target="_blank" class="icon none">间谍卫星</a>。</p><p>武器专家表示，朝鲜近年来的大部分武器试验<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-launches-unknown-projectile-off-its-east-coast-south-korea-says-11642381386" target="_blank" class="icon none">都旨在加强短程导弹</a>，其中大部分都具有核能力。平壤声称成功地从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-fires-ballistic-missile-off-east-coast-south-koreas-military-says-11634611489" target="_blank" class="icon none">潜艇</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-fired-unidentified-projectile-off-its-east-coast-south-says-11642145343" target="_blank" class="icon none">火车车厢</a>发射武器，并且有能力操纵导弹躲避美国或韩国的防御。</p><p>许多新推出的短程导弹都依赖固体燃料。对于洲际弹道导弹来说，使用液体燃料发动机意味着在发射前必须派出一队车辆进行运输和加油，从而更容易被发现并可能被阻止。</p><p>根据美国情报界 2023 年 3 月发布的年度威胁评估，金正恩“几乎肯定将核武器和洲际弹道导弹视为其独裁统治的最终保证，并且无意放弃这些计划”。</p><h3>朝鲜最后一次发射导弹是什么时候？</h3><p>朝鲜一直在进行武器试验而几乎不受惩罚。</p><p>金正恩<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-suspends-nuclear-long-range-missile-tests-and-plans-to-close-nuclear-test-site-1524264301" target="_blank" class="icon none">在 2018 年 4 月的和平谈判</a>中承诺不进行核试验或洲际弹道导弹试验。到 2020 年初，这位独裁者透露，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-says-north-korea-will-unveil-a-new-strategic-weapon-11577832679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">不再感到</a>受到自我暂停的约束。但在该声明发布后两年多的时间里，重大挑衅行为并未真正卷土重来。</p><p>在金正恩十多年的统治期间，朝鲜加速了该国的武器开发。根据华盛顿智库战略与国际研究中心的数据，朝鲜进行了 190 多次导弹发射和核试验，其中 150 多次是自金正恩 2011 年底上台以来进行的，该中心的数据库可追溯到 1984 年。</p><h3>美国对朝鲜导弹试验有何反应？</h3><p>自从乔治·H·W·布什总统入主白宫以来，华盛顿和平壤一直举行无核化谈判，而朝鲜仍然由金正恩的祖父、创始人金日成领导。此前的协议试图冻结生产、允许现场检查或拆除设施，以换取援助或其他资源。但在朝鲜拒绝遵守或进行军事挑衅后，这些安排破裂了。</p><p>时任总统唐纳德·特朗普采取了不同的做法，将通常由工作级别官员进行的谈判转变为领导人级别的外交。特朗普政府淡化了朝鲜在 2019 年春季恢复的武器试验，因为其中不包括洲际弹道导弹或核弹。特朗普和高级官员表示，没有进行远程测试是美国做法成功的标志。美国前国家安全顾问约翰·博尔顿等其他人表示，这些测试<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bolton-says-north-korea-missile-tests-broke-u-n-ban-11558756009?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">违反了联合国的限制</a>。</p><p>朝鲜无视拜登政府一再提出的随时随地无条件会面的提议。</p><p>如果没有一项能够放松制裁（限制朝鲜进入外国银行和全球贸易）的核协议，金正恩就无法兑现重振在疫情期间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-koreas-economy-hit-harder-than-it-has-been-in-decades-11608300202?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">崩溃的朝鲜经济</a>的承诺。该国正面临<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-suffers-one-of-its-worst-food-crises-in-decades-ee25aa86?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">几十年来最严重的粮食危机之一</a>，饥饿和饥饿现象普遍存在。</p><p> 2022 年 5 月就任的保守派韩国总统尹锡烈支持对朝鲜的武器试验和侵犯人权行为采取更具对抗性的立场。这与他的前任、左倾文在寅有所不同，文在寅奉行支持接触的政策。</p><p>在尹先生的领导下，韩国经常将朝鲜的导弹试验称为挑衅，寻求<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/japan-and-south-korea-leaders-meet-one-on-one-for-first-time-since-2019-11663841992?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">改善与日本的关系</a>，并在中断近四年后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-south-korea-revive-live-military-drills-after-four-year-hiatus-11661074202?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">恢复与美国的大规模实地演习</a>。</p><h3>拜登总统对朝鲜的立场是什么？</h3><p>拜登总统将朝鲜称为美国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/biden-press-conference-live-updates-analysis/card/W9wyilDsb86eqzEySPCI?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最大的外交政策威胁</a>。他主张将压力与他所谓的原则外交相结合。他宣布停止无条件举行峰会，他说这无异于拥抱暴徒。拜登表示，只有平壤有诚意并承诺削减核武库，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-open-to-meeting-north-koreas-kim-pledges-deterrence-with-seoul-11653129309?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">才会与金正恩坐下来</a>。</p><p>拜登于 2023 年 4 月对白宫进行国事访问期间接待了尹恩惠，两国在会上达成了所谓的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-south-korea-pledge-cooperation-on-potential-use-of-nuclear-arms-ceeecec9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">《华盛顿宣言》</a> 。作为该协议的一部分，韩国重申其不发展自己核武器的承诺。作为回报，美国承诺向该地区派遣战略资产，例如<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-its-biggest-sub-to-korean-peninsula-in-message-to-north-and-south-d998518?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">核潜艇</a>和 B-52 轰炸机。核磋商小组的成立旨在让首尔首次在有关美国可能使用核武器应对朝鲜袭击的审议中拥有更大的发言权。</p><p>拜登在尹访问期间表示，朝鲜的任何核攻击都将导致金氏政权的终结。</p><p>据首尔情报机构称，朝鲜重返谈判的要求包括放松制裁，以便金氏政权能够出口矿产并进口更多精炼燃料。但根据 2021 年 8 月的评估，韩国立法者在简报中分享了这份必备清单，其中还包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-is-willing-to-talk-but-first-it-wants-fuel-suits-and-liquor-11627990817?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">精美西装和优质酒类</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1A143373-3034-4A8C-BC6E-4D8C2EB204BF&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fnorth-korea-nuclear-weapons-missiles-explained-11610712018&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">从更强大的洲际弹道导弹到高超音速导弹，朝鲜除了核弹和潜艇外还展示了新武器。 《华尔街日报》审视了该政权不断增长的武器库，看看它向世界传达了什么信息。综合：Diana Chan<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div><p><strong>写信给</strong>Timothy W. Martin，邮箱为<a href="mailto:timothy.martin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">timothy.martin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 08:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-nuclear-weapons-missiles-explained-11610712018</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-nuclear-weapons-missiles-explained-11610712018<author><![CDATA[Timothy W. Martin]]></author><category> #nk实验</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>工业品</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>核武器计划</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>贸易壁垒/限制</category><category>武器计划</category><category>#NK实验</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>乔·拜登</category><category>金正恩</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>核武器计划</category><category>政治</category><category>贸易壁垒</category><category>限制</category><category>武器计划</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[State Department Orders Partial Evacuation of U.S. Embassy in Niger]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国是上周政变后最新采取行动的西方国家<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106229"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828747?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国国务院发言人表示，尼日尔首都尼亚美目前的局势不稳定但平静。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ISSIFOU DJIBO/EPA/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106229"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/vivian-salama" itemprop="url" rel="author">维维安·萨拉马</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 2 日晚上 9:45（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>华盛顿——美国国务院周三下令非紧急美国政府雇员和符合条件的家庭成员离开尼日尔，原因是担心军政府上周拘留该国当选总统后紧张局势可能升级。</p><p>美国国务院更新了其警告，该警告此前曾警告美国公民因犯罪、恐怖主义和绑架而重新考虑前往尼日尔的旅行。目前尚不清楚有多少美国人居住在尼日尔，国务院表示正在评估可以采取哪些措施来确保所有美国人的安全。</p><p> “国务院命令非紧急美国政府人员和符合条件的家庭成员暂时离开美国驻尼亚美大使馆，”该部门在一份声明中表示。 “商业航班选择有限。我们更新了旅行警告以反映这一点，并通知美国公民，鉴于人员减少，我们只能向尼日尔的美国公民提供紧急援助。”</p><p>周三早些时候，美国国务院发言人马修·米勒表示，使馆人员和海外美国公民的安全是政府的首要任务，尼日尔首都目前的局势不稳定但平静。<br> “我们不断监测现场事件，并根据保护我们人员的适当措施做出决定，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828749?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">从尼日尔撤离的欧洲人和美国人于周三抵达意大利。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：雷莫·卡西利/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>The State Department said the embassy in Niamey remains open for limited emergency services to US citizens and that it would continuously re-examine the situation as security conditions permit.</p><p> While it wasn&#39;t immediately clear why the department changed course, a one-week deadline imposed on Sunday by the 15-nation Economic Community of West African States for the military junta to cede power is approaching. The bloc said it would consider a military intervention to oust the coup plotters and restore democratic rule in the vast Saharan country if that deadline wasn&#39;t met.</p><p> On Tuesday, European governments began evacuating their citizens from Niger after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-general-declares-himself-leader-as-russian-mercenary-hails-coup-d47efa68" target="_blank" class="icon none">last week&#39;s coup</a> in the West African country <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">triggered a tense standoff</a> between Moscow&#39;s allies in the region and countries that have worked more closely with the US and other Western powers.</p><p> The evacuations, led by France, Niger&#39;s former colonial ruler, show that European governments expect their citizens to be at higher risk in the country, which <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679" target="_blank" class="icon none">has been central</a> to US efforts to combat Islamist militants in the Sahel, the semiarid strip south of the Sahara. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9B8EB2F8-7751-46ED-8D36-E964233A2505&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fstate-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">国务卿安东尼·布林肯周六表示，尼日尔的军事政变危及了美国价值数亿美元的援助和安全支持。欧盟还暂停了与尼日尔的安全合作和财政支持。照片：达伦·英格兰/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Last week, US Secretary of State Antony Blinken expressed support for Niger&#39;s President Mohamed Bazoum</p> during a visit to Australia and warned that Washington could cut support to Niger if the military held on to power. However, Blinken and other US officials have stopped short of describing the events in Niger as a coup, which would immediately freeze aid under US law.<p></p><p> Blinken spoke with Bazoum on Wednesday, one of several calls he has held with him since the Nigerien leader was placed under house arrest. According to a readout from the State Department, Blinken reiterated US commitment to “the restoration of the democratically elected government.” He told Bazoum that the US is “dedicated to finding a peaceful resolution that ensures that Niger remains a strong partner in security and development in the region.”</p><p> The US has spent more than $500 million since 2012 to build up and train Niger&#39;s armed forces. The vast West African country hosts American drones and American commandos, who, in addition to training, advise Nigerien special forces during <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">combat missions against insurgents</a> .</p><p> On Saturday, the EU&#39;s foreign-policy chief, Josep Borrell,</p> said the bloc had frozen budgetary support as well as military assistance to Niger <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">in response to the rebellion</a> and would continue to recognize Bazoum as the country&#39;s legitimate president.<p></p><p> The EU also has a training mission in Niger. The freeze affects that mission as well as significant parts of the 503 million euros, equivalent to about $550 million, that the EU had planned to contribute to Niger&#39;s budget and population-targeted projects in the country between 2021 and 2024. The EU will continue sending humanitarian aid to Niger.</p><p> The decision by the State Department comes days after it ordered the departure of nonemergency personnel from Haiti as the security situation there deteriorates.</p><p> Write to Vivian Salama at <a href="mailto:vivian.salama@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">vivian.salama@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 01:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-us-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-us-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd<author><![CDATA[Vivian Salama]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category> Society/Community</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>International Relations</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>Military Action</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category> society</category><category> community</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>military action</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Brazil’s Central Bank Cuts Selic to 13.25%]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The bank opted for a half-point cut as the country&#39;s inflation outlook improves <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106228"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828746?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Five members of the central bank&#39;s Copom monetary policy committee voted for a half-point cut, while the other four voted for a quarter-point cut.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ton Molina/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106228"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paulo-trevisani" itemprop="url" rel="author">Paulo Trevisani</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jeffrey-t-lewis" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jeffrey T. Lewis</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 7:27 pm ET <span class="divider">|</span> <span class="wsjpro-label">WSJ Pro</span> </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazils-central-bank-cuts-selic-to-13-25-3fbb872b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Brazil&#39;s central bank cut its benchmark interest rate by half a percentage point, the first change to the rate in a year, and said it could be the first of a series of cuts meant to substantially reduce one of the world&#39;s highest interest rates.</p><p> The bank&#39;s monetary policy committee, or Copom, reduced its key Selic rate to 13.25% from 13.75%, after raising it to that level in August 2022. The move reverses a rate-increase cycle launched in March 2021 when the Selic was at a record low of 2%.</p><p> The bank said it considered cutting the Selic by a quarter-point, but chose to make a larger cut because of continuing improvement in the country&#39;s inflation outlook.</p><p> “If the scenario evolves as expected, the committee members unanimously anticipate further reductions of the same magnitude in the next meetings, and it judges that this pace is appropriate to keep the necessary contractionary monetary policy for the disinflationary process,” the Central Bank of Brazil said in a statement.</p><p> Five members of the Copom voted for the half-point cut, while the other four voted for a quarter-point cut.</p><p> The likely start of a rate-cutting cycle comes after the bank&#39;s efforts to slow consumer price increases helped bring the 12-month inflation rate down from an almost 19-year high. In June, the rate stood at 3.16%, down from 12.13% in April 2022, which was the slowest pace for inflation growth since October 2020. Consumer prices declined 0.08% in June from May.</p><p> Many economists had been expecting a cut of 25 basis points.但交易所交易基金提供商 Global X 的高级投资组合经理马尔科姆·多尔森 (Malcolm Dorson) 在一份报告中表示，近期通胀放缓似乎让政策制定者更加大胆。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “The more aggressive 50bp move indicates the Copom&#39;s comfort with the economic landscape,” he said. “Given the previous prudence of this group of directors, the 50bp move signals that Brazil is off to the races.”</p><p> Even with the larger-than-expected cut Wednesday, the gap between inflation and the Selic rate remains wide and even deeper cuts may be in store, said Gino Olivares, chief economist at Azimut Brasil Wealth Management.</p><p> If the central bank trims half a percentage point for the next three meetings, “we will have the Selic at 11.75% at the end of the year, which is still a contractionist level,” Olivares said. “未来，他们将不得不评估是否加快宽松步伐。”</p><p> The central bank began raising the Selic after inflation started to pick up toward the end of 2020 and then rose faster as the Brazil&#39;s economy recovered from the pandemic-induced slowdown. The Russian invasion of Ukraine later pushed inflation even higher as energy and food prices gained amid supply disruptions.</p><p> Higher interest rates are now having the expected effect on inflation and the economy, and other factors are also helping calm concerns at the central bank, said Matheus Pizzani, an economist at brokerage CM Capital Markets.</p><p> “The more recent evolution of inflation has been closer to what was hoped,” Pizzani said. High rates are helping slow the economy, concerns about the new Brazilian government&#39;s fiscal policies have eased, and the outlook for services inflation is improving, he added.</p><p> Inflation expectations in Brazil have come down, as measured by the central bank&#39;s weekly survey of economists, although they remain above the bank&#39;s targets. The bank&#39;s target for this year, for example, is 3.25% and the median forecast of 153 economists in the most recent survey is for consumer prices to rise 4.84% this year.</p><p> Some economists say part of the current decline in Brazil&#39;s 12-month inflation readings are temporary, stemming from fuel tax cuts the government applied last year. CM Capital 的皮萨尼表示，这种影响可能会在未来几个月内消失，导致总体通胀指标可能在经济放缓的情况下上升。</p><p> “Inflation readings will increasingly reflect actual supply and demand imbalances,” he said. He sees inflation bouncing back to 4.8% in December, before falling to 3.8% a year later.</p><p> Write to Paulo Trevisani at <a href="mailto:paulo.trevisani@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">paulo.trevisani@wsj.com</a> and Jeffrey T. Lewis at <a href="mailto:jeffrey.lewis@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jeffrey.lewis@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 23:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazils-central-bank-cuts-selic-to-13-25-3fbb872b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazils-central-bank-cuts-selic-to-13-25-3fbb872b<author><![CDATA[Paulo TrevisaniJeffrey T. Lewis]]></author><category>银行业</category><category>Central Banking</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>Financial Services</category><category> Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category> Inflation Figures/Price Indices</category><category>货币政策</category><category>Interest Rates</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>PRO</category><category> WSJ-PRO-CB</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> economic performance</category><category> indicators</category><category> inflation figures</category><category> price indices</category><category>货币政策</category><category>interest rates</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>银行业</category><category>central banking</category><category>信用</category><category>financial services </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Canadian Prime Minister Trudeau, Wife Separate]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Married for 18 years, they have three children <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104884"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828395?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Despite the separation, Justin Trudeau and Sophie Grégoire Trudeau plan to vacation together as a family soon.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: anna moneymaker/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104884"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">Paul Vieira</a></span> by</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 2, 2023 4:44 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-prime-minister-trudeau-wife-sophie-gregoire-separate-6b7c6ed7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> OTTAWA—Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau and his wife, Sophie Grégoire Trudeau, said Wednesday that they have separated after 18 years of marriage.</p><p> The couple issued statements on their respective Instagram accounts. “Sophie and I would like to share the fact that after many meaningful and difficult conversations, we have made the decision to separate,” Justin Trudeau, 51,<a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CvctRHlrcL9/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">said on Instagram</a> . Sophie Grégoire Trudeau&#39;s<a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CvctRb3uszw/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Instagram post</a> was nearly identical. They both asked for privacy.</p><p> A separate statement from the couple, issued by the prime minister&#39;s office, said they have signed a legal separation agreement, and they ensured proper legal and ethical standards were followed.</p><p> “They remain a close family and Sophie and the Prime Minister are focused on raising their kids in a safe, loving and collaborative environment,” the statement from Justin Trudeau&#39;s office said. “Both parents will be a constant presence in their children&#39;s lives and Canadians can expect to often see the family together.”</p><p> The family will be together on vacation, beginning next week, his office said.</p><p> Justin Trudeau and Sophie Grégoire Trudeau have three children: two boys, ages 15 and 9, and a 14-year-old daughter.</p><p> One of the last public appearances featuring the couple was in Ottawa on July 1, when they attended a ceremony to celebrate Canada&#39;s 156th birthday.</p><p> The two met in June 2003 at a charity gala. Justin Trudeau, in the 2014 memoir “Common Ground,” said they chatted and flirted for much of the evening. Months later, they went on a dinner date at an Afghan restaurant in Montreal&#39;s Plateau district. “I felt a giddy sense that Sophie would be the last woman I ever dated,” he said in the memoir.</p><p> They were married in Montreal on May 28, 2005, in what local media described as a glamorous service. After the service, the couple took a drive in a restored 1960 Mercedes-Benz 300 SL roadster, which had belonged to Justin Trudeau&#39;s father, former Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau.</p><p></p><p> Sophie Grégoire Trudeau, 48, grew up in Montreal and earned degrees at Montreal&#39;s McGill University and the Université de Montreal. She worked as a television host and later became an entertainment correspondent in Quebec. The Liberal Party website describes Sophie Grégoire Trudeau as a mentor on a variety of causes, including teenage self-esteem, women&#39;s and girls&#39; rights, eating disorders and mental health.</p><p> “I can tell you right away that no marriage is easy,” she said in <a href="https://globalnews.ca/news/1897750/a-family-affair-canadas-next-first-lady-lunch-with-sophie-gregoire-trudeau/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">a March 2015 interview with Global News</a> , about seven months before her husband won his first election to serve as prime minister. “I&#39;m almost kind of proud of the fact that we&#39;ve had hardship, yes, because we want authenticity. We want truth.”</p><p> Justin Trudeau said in 2016 that he was proud of what his wife had done to champion women&#39;s rights and help charitable causes. “She continues to have a lot to offer, not just to the government but to Canadians.”</p><p> In May 1977, Pierre Trudeau and wife Margaret Trudeau announced their separation. “I remember the bad times as a succession of painful emotional snapshots,” Justin Trudeau said in his 2014 memoir about the separation. “The demands imposed by the life my parents were leading affected them far more than the ordinary stress of parenthood.”</p><p> Write to Paul Vieira at <a href="mailto:Paul.Vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Paul.Vieira@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 20:44:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-prime-minister-trudeau-wife-sophie-gregoire-separate-6b7c6ed7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-prime-minister-trudeau-wife-sophie-gregoire-separate-6b7c6ed7<author><![CDATA[Paul Vieira]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Justin Trudeau</category><category> Sophie Grégoire Trudeau</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Iran Begins Two-Day Shutdown as Heat Wave Worsens]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Climate change poses specific security challenges for the Islamic Republic, which has faced unrest over water shortages <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104925"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828144?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Many residents of Tehran are staying home as temperatures in Iran soar.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: WANA NEWS AGENCY/via REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104925"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sune Engel Rasmussen</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name">Aresu Eqbali</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 2:11 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-begins-two-day-shutdown-as-heat-wave-worsens-e756dcfc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> TEHRAN—Neighborhoods across Tehran fell quiet Wednesday as temperatures surpassing 100 degrees Fahrenheit bore down on Iran&#39;s capital.</p><p> Many residents stayed home after the government declared an emergency two-day shutdown, closing banks, exchange shops and government offices and calling on private businesses to follow suit. Toward the north, roads leading out of the city to cooler regions were clogged with people seeking relief from the heat.</p><p> The national holiday, announced Tuesday, was an unusual response to the increasingly <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rising-temperatures-turns-middle-east-region-into-climate-hot-spot-11663172120?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">frequent heat waves</a> hitting the country, which in the south have pushed temperatures above 120 degrees Fahrenheit.</p><p> The health ministry advised children, the elderly and those with underlying health conditions to stay indoors. Other government departments pleaded with people to consume less electricity and refrain from using power-hungry devices except in the morning and late at night to ensure there was enough power to go around for Iran&#39;s nearly 90 million people.</p><p> Residents with holiday homes in the hills north of the capital and along the Caspian Sea bundled into cars as early as Tuesday evening after the two-day special holiday was announced. Grocery stores, restaurants and shopping malls largely stayed open, though traffic within the capital was noticeably thinner than usual.</p><p> In a region scorched by global warming, Iran is particularly vulnerable to the effects of climate change. It is dominated by an arid and semiarid climate, marked by low rain and snowfall.</p><p> While <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraq-tests-u-s-sanctions-with-oil-for-gas-deal-with-iran-c318b917?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">US sanctions</a> to some extent hamper Iran&#39;s ability to mitigate the impact of global warming, successive governments have failed to invest in climate-friendly initiatives such as solar energy or more efficient agricultural technology. In the winter, when a lid of cold air captures the smog, the capital of Tehran is enveloped in a yellow haze emanating from antiquated cars belching exhaust from low-quality fuel. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828142?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Temperatures in Tehran rose above 100 degrees Fahrenheit on Wednesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: WANA NEWS AGENCY/via REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Iranian authorities have warned that the western lake of Urmia, which was once the Middle East&#39;s largest lake but has been shrinking since the mid-1990s, is at risk of fully drying up if dam construction and other agricultural projects aren&#39;t halted. The Iranian government has dug a 20-mile tunnel to transfer water into the lake from a nearby basin.</p><p> Iran faces a conundrum, however, with dams and irrigation projects vital to assisting a struggling agricultural sector that already has lost billions of dollars to the shocks of climate change. In a climate zone like Iran&#39;s, each one-degree increase in temperature can reduce crop production by 10%, according to the United Nations, worsening food security when the war in Ukraine is already badly <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">disrupting global grain markets</a> .</p><p> The rest of Iran&#39;s economy—hampered by US sanctions—is ill-equipped to adapt. In the year to March 2022, power outages cost the country $7 billion to $8 billion in non-oil exports, according to the country&#39;s chamber of commerce, industries, mines and agriculture.</p><p> This year&#39;s temperature surge, with July logged as the warmest month on record, has brought pain across the Middle East.</p><p> Iraq last year introduced prolonged national holidays to protect employees from the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-iraq-tries-to-beat-the-heat-u-s-renews-sanctions-waiver-on-power-from-iran-11560860766?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">scorching heat</a> . Temperatures there were this week expected to surpass 120 degrees Fahrenheit in large parts of the country, amplifying pressure on the country&#39;s ailing electricity grid.</p><p> Iraq partly depends on gas imports from Iran for its electricity, but has struggled to pay for them due to US sanctions on Tehran. As debts built up, Iran in June cut gas supplies to Iraq, plunging its neighbor into blackouts and power shortages just as the scorching summer heat set in. The government in Baghdad last month announced a new barter arrangement, in which Iraq would pay for Iranian gas with oil, testing the resolve of the US to enforce its sanctions.</p><p> Egypt last month introduced scheduled, rolling power cuts to relieve pressure on the nation&#39;s power grid, saying the cuts would last no more than two hours a day at times of surging energy consumption, and warned the population against using elevators at certain times of the day. The government also told most civil servants to work remotely once a week beginning this Sunday, and encouraged private companies to take similar steps.</p><p> In Lebanon, the effect of sweltering temperatures has been compounded by longstanding electricity rationing. The government grid supplies only a few hours of electricity a day, making residents living through a severe economic crisis dependent on private generators to cool down. The country has also been plagued by wildfires in recent weeks.</p><p> Iranian authorities, though, are especially sensitive to the security challenges posed by climate change. In recent years the government has faced simmering unrest over water shortages, caused by a combination of drought and government mismanagement. People have protested particularly in the restive and arid southeastern part of the country, but also in the dried-up bed of an iconic river in the central city of Isfahan. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828143?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A man rested in a closed store in Zanjan, Iran, on Tuesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rouzbeh Fouladi/ZUMA Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Sistan-Baluchistan, a border region near Afghanistan and Pakistan, is a source of particular concern. It is home to a Sunni Muslim ethnic minority with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a history of hostility to the central government</a> in Tehran, and was a driving force in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-protests-hijab-11675177547?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a range of protests</a> that swept the country last year. Baluch communities are increasingly short on drinking water, and on Monday, hundreds of residents protested in the streets.</p><p> At the heart of the protests is a decadeslong water conflict with neighboring Afghanistan.</p><p> According to a 1973 treaty, the two countries share water from the Helmand River flowing from the Hindu Kush mountains in the central Afghan highlands. Iranian authorities have for years accused the Afghan government, now controlled by the Taliban, of providing less than its fair share of water, a charge Afghanistan denies. The head of Iran&#39;s department of environment on Wednesday said Afghanistan had provided Iran with less than 2% of the water it was entitled to.</p><p> Before the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-taliban-are-here-the-final-days-before-kabuls-collapse-11629505499?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Taliban takeover of Afghanistan</a> , the US-backed government of Ashraf Ghani invested tens of millions of dollars into dam projects that divert water from the Helmand River to irrigate Afghan farmlands.</p><p> Iranian President Ebrahim Raisi in May warned the Taliban not to violate the water rights of the Iranian people, and called on the Taliban to allow Iranian hydrologists to check the water levels of the Helmand River to ensure Iran wasn&#39;t cheated of its share. Days later, deadly clashes broke out on the border, killing two Iranian security officers and a Taliban border guard.</p><p> The Taliban have continued to operate the dams.</p><p> The Iranian government, meanwhile, warned people that further shutdowns were possible if the heat continued.</p><p> The Iranian minister of interior, Ahmad Vahidi, said the government was willing to call another public holiday in the future if health authorities thought it was needed to save lives.</p><p> “We hope it won&#39;t be necessary to shut down the country,” he said, according to state media.</p><p> Write to Sune Engel Rasmussen at <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 18:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-begins-two-day-shutdown-as-heat-wave-worsens-e756dcfc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-begins-two-day-shutdown-as-heat-wave-worsens-e756dcfc<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel Rasmussen]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category> Global/World Issues</category><category> Natural Resource Scarcity</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Environmental Pollution</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>climate change</category><category> natural environment</category><category> global</category><category> world issues</category><category> natural resource scarcity</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>environmental pollution </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Drawn-Out Ukraine War Opens New Risks for China]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Beijing&#39;s expected attendance at peace meeting could show any evolution in its viewpoint <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828293/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="周一，顿涅茨克俄罗斯控制区一处被毁的房屋。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A destroyed house in a Russian-controlled area of Donetsk on Monday. ALEXANDER ERMOCHENKO/REUTERS <span>ALEXANDER ERMOCHENKO/REUTERS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104474"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001104474"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-t-areddy" itemprop="url" rel="author">James T. Areddy</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 12:37 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> China has given Russian President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> important diplomatic and economic backing for his war on Ukraine. But as the conflict <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-war-becomes-grinding-fight-medics-battle-to-save-soldiers-in-ukraine-b04a976a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">drags into its 18th month</a> with no clear sign of victory or capitulation on either side, Beijing faces an increasingly complicated set of risks that give it more incentive to push Moscow and Kyiv toward peace talks.</p><p> The shocking but short-lived rebellion by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-wagner-revolt-questions-of-blame-in-vladimir-putins-inner-circle-64c541ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Russian paramilitary group Wagner</a> in June has raised new questions about Putin&#39;s hold on power and the possibility of a future Russia without the autocrat whom China&#39;s leader Xi Jinping has called <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/xi-and-putin-a-friendship-forged-against-the-west-866dfcf1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">his best friend</a> . It has also brought new focus to the risks of Beijing&#39;s support for Moscow.</p><p> Xi is expected to dispatch Chinese peace envoy Li Hui to a Ukraine-backed international conference aimed at outlining the terms of a possible peace deal, according to European and US officials. That would mark a significant shift, as Beijing stayed away from the group&#39;s first meeting, held in Copenhagen in June.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-to-host-ukraine-peace-talks-as-part-of-western-effort-to-woo-global-south-244f03f0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">This weekend&#39;s gathering in Saudi Arabia</a> , aimed at outlining principles that should frame a possible peace deal, includes a range of world powers sympathetic to Kyiv and excludes Russia. The spokeswoman for Russia&#39;s Foreign Ministry on Wednesday said the meeting was “a hoax” intended to create an anti-Moscow coalition, according to Russian state news agency TASS.</p><p> Chinese participation would present a rare opportunity for US-China engagement over the war as President Biden&#39;s national security adviser, Jake Sullivan, is also expected to attend. Attendees will be watching for any sign that Beijing&#39;s thinking about the conflict, and its end, has evolved. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="471" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828287?width=700&amp;height=471" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Russian President Vladimir Putin hosted Chinese President Xi Jinping at the Kremlin in Moscow in March.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Grigory Sysoev/Sputnik</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Beijing&#39;s flirtation with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warns-china-could-arm-russia-as-ukraine-seeks-to-repel-advances-in-east-a5fd3e9e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">red lines set by the US</a> around wartime trade with Russia has strained its relations with the West and led to increased scrutiny, including in European capitals that China has sought to charm. And China continues to signal concern that nuclear weapons could be deployed—both <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-rebukes-russias-nuclear-threats-in-ukraine-for-first-time-11667585543?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a veiled warning to Moscow</a> and a threat to the West to limit support for Ukraine.</p><p> China&#39;s unease was on display last month at the United Nations General Assembly, when its deputy permanent representative, Geng Shuang, outlined stark concerns about the enduring war. “The Ukraine crisis has dragged on to this day with no signs of easing on the ground, military logic still prevailing, and slow progress in peace talks, which all point to a worrying prospect,” Geng said. He called for peace talks to promote “an early cease-fire and political solution.”</p><p> Geng&#39;s lengthy tally of the broader risks of the war, including nuclear-weapons use, contrasted with a presentation by Geng to the UN in March, shortly after Beijing publicized a 12-point position paper on resolving the conflict. During that earlier presentation, Geng blasted the US for what he called “Russiaphobia.”</p><p> In his latest UN presentation, Geng minimized finger-pointing and instead concentrated on issues like food security, which he mentioned three times. Days earlier Putin said Russia would pull out of a deal to permit safe <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Black Sea passage of Ukrainian grain</a> . China has been the biggest market for that output.</p><p> “Based on official reportage, the sense one gets is that China&#39;s concerns remain around escalation and spillovers,” according to Manoj Kewalramani, a China studies fellow at India-based think tank Takshashila Institution, who tracks statements by Beijing officials.</p><p> Kewalramani also pointed to a recent commentary published in the Communist Party&#39;s People&#39;s Daily newspaper expressing concern that the US was using the war as a pretext to open new fronts to confront Beijing, such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/natos-new-focus-on-china-creates-internal-tension-about-mission-creep-a4a1a77e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">expanding the North Atlantic Treaty Organization&#39;s mandate to Asia</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7B2C2519-2B65-4FA4-8474-F1A9681DEF8E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> China is now the world&#39;s largest auto exporter with Russia becoming its biggest buyer this year. WSJ explains how Chinese car brands profited from Moscow&#39;s invasion of Ukraine and Western sanctions. Illustration: Kalvin Ng<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“The US has attempted to link the Ukraine crisis with Asia-Pacific affairs, threatening European countries to &#39;decouple&#39; from China and pressuring them to participate in its so-called Indo-Pacific strategy,” according to the commentary by Zhang Jian, a vice president at the Beijing-based think tank China Institutes of Contemporary International Relations.</p><p> While neither side in Ukraine appears to have the upper hand, a prolonged conflict promises diplomatic and economic ramifications for China. Whereas Beijing has sought to position itself as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sticks-close-to-russia-as-it-makes-cautious-diplomatic-push-4416eed8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a peacemaker</a> , it has sometimes misstepped, for instance when in April its top diplomat in France appeared to call into question the legal basis for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-ambassador-to-france-says-ex-soviet-states-lack-basis-for-sovereignty-8a46ad7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the sovereignty of some former Soviet republics</a> . Now diplomatic endeavors are clouded by the mysterious departure of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Xi&#39;s handpicked foreign minister</a> , Qin Gang.</p><p> Xi has demonstrated little follow-through to his springtime effort to mediate in the conflict, which included dispatching diplomats to Europe to promote February&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-avoids-chinas-belt-and-road-forum-keeping-a-distance-from-xi-and-putin-14f6253b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">12-point position paper</a> . Xi hasn&#39;t repeated <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-xi-makes-first-call-to-zelensky-since-russian-invasion-b784bb7f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">his single wartime telephone conversation</a> three months ago with Ukrainian President President</p> Volodymyr Zelensky, despite <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-xi-arrives-in-moscow-as-beijing-seeks-to-position-itself-as-a-peacemaker-8f11d364?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">continued dialogue with Putin</a> .<p></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-pushing-ukraine-cease-fire-gets-cool-reception-in-europe-614774dd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beijing has failed to convince Western officials</a> that it can be seen as neutral in the conflict due to Xi&#39;s tight relationship with Putin. Distrust of Xi and China is widespread around the world, according to a newly published survey by Pew Research Center that said a median of 71% of respondents in 24 nations viewed the country as not contributing to global peace and stability.</p><p> A dragged-out war <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is negative for China&#39;s economy</a> , its global development goals and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-avoids-chinas-belt-and-road-forum-keeping-a-distance-from-xi-and-putin-14f6253b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its image in Europe</a> , but Beijing hasn&#39;t clearly adjusted its messaging, according to Philippe Le Corre, a senior fellow at the Asia Society Policy Institute. “No one is impressed with the &#39;12-point peace plan&#39; nor was anyone impressed with Qin Gang when he visited Europe,” said Le Corre. Critics of the plan&#39;s call for a cease-fire say the effect would be <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-new-poll-89-of-ukrainians-reject-ceding-land-to-reach-peace-with-russia-11656504002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to cede to Russia</a> the roughly 20% chunk of Ukraine it controls, including Crimea, which Moscow annexed in 2014.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allies-stick-together-to-confront-russia-and-chinafor-now-76156bf7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China is engaged in a “balancing act”</a> of being supportive of Russia while trying to present itself as a neutral player and a force for peace, “and that strain is increasingly apparent,” US Secretary of State Antony Blinken told Richard Haass of the Council on Foreign Relations shortly after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-jinping-to-meet-blinken-monday-as-u-s-china-resume-high-level-engagement-c898f541?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">his June sit-down with Xi</a> .</p><p> Still, Beijing&#39;s “certain amount of influence” with Moscow could be useful once diplomacy to end the war has realistic prospects of achieving results, Blinken said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="427" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828286?width=700&amp;height=427" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chinese leader Xi Jinping is expected to send Chinese peace envoy Li Hui, in Moscow in May, to a Ukraine-backed international conference in Saudi Arabia.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: maxim shipenkov/epa/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A welcome to China reflects the Biden administration&#39;s efforts to re-engage, but any notion that a mediating role for Beijing would drive a wedge between it and Moscow is misplaced, according to a recent letter to Blinken from 10 Republican senators. They called for blocking Beijing out of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-china-meeting-shows-no-breakthrough-to-end-russian-invasion-f71a871d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">any Ukraine settlement</a> by saying, “The administration&#39;s policy should not allow China to absolve itself for its support of Russia or use this war for its longer-term political and economic benefit.”</p><p> François Godement, a special adviser to the French think tank Institut Montaigne, said Beijing isn&#39;t trusted as a neutral party in Europe, and he cast doubt on its diplomatic acumen, which appeared to get a boost in March when <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-brokered-deal-between-iran-saudi-arabia-marks-a-new-middle-east-d1eaf94e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China brokered a deal for Saudi Arabia and Iran</a> to re-establish diplomatic ties.</p><p> “China&#39;s real strength lies elsewhere: in its vastly increased commercial and tech attractiveness on all parties, and in the resulting impossibility to ignore China as an unavoidable partner with the capacity to reward or to punish,” Godement wrote recently.</p><p> Xi hasn&#39;t reacted publicly to the challenge Putin appeared to face during the Wagner rebellion, but analysts say it likely rattled him. The policy newsletter GZERO Daily recently outlined why China&#39;s leader might be compelled to press Moscow to end the war: “He&#39;s giving Putin the &#39;off ramp&#39; the Russian president can&#39;t (or won&#39;t) create for himself,” it said.</p><p> Xi appears unwavering in his support for Russia, for instance meeting a Putin ally in July—the head of the upper chamber of the Russian Parliament, Valentina Matvienko— then days later <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">snubbing President Biden&#39;s climate envoy</a> , John Kerry. More quietly, China in July also welcomed to Beijing a Ukrainian trade envoy, Taras Kachka, with a vow to increase the country&#39;s imports from Ukraine.</p><p> The Chinese narrative “retains just enough ambiguity that the Chinese Communist Party could claim later they never backed Putin&#39;s war,” according to Godement.</p><p> Beijing faces scrutiny of its deepening trade with Russia, at a time when Western capitals are looking to further punish Moscow for the Ukraine invasion by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-economy-is-starting-to-come-undone-431a2878?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">freezing it out of the global economy</a> and limiting its access to weaponry. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828290?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China&#39;s deputy permanent representative to the UN, Geng Shuang, last month stressed the need for food security, days after Russia said it would pull out of a deal to permit safe Black Sea passage of Ukrainian grain.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bianca Otero/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A US report in July by the Office of the Director of National Intelligence said government-owned companies in China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-aids-russias-war-in-ukraine-trade-data-shows-11675466360?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have exported to Russia</a> ship navigation equipment, jamming technology and jet-fighter parts, while importing energy and underwriting insurance on Russian ships. The report also cited press findings that China has supplied drones and semiconductors to Russia.</p><p> But the US intelligence report said the use of shell companies in China, misrepresented documentation and complex supply chains make it difficult to know how much China has helped Russia evade sanctions and export controls.</p><p> During a recent two-week trip around China, Scott Kennedy of the Washington think tank Center for Strategic and International Studies didn&#39;t hear any serious ideas for ending the war, only that Ukraine should accept a cease-fire. Kennedy said one expert he met warned that the West should understand that Russia could deploy tactical nuclear weapons out of desperation.</p><p> “The takeaway is unsurprising. Instead of criticizing Russia and proposing it come to its senses and withdraw, they offer this as another reason for the US and West to stop arming Ukraine,” according to Kennedy.</p><p> The fizzling of the Wagner revolt and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the limited progress of Ukraine&#39;s offensive</a> may give China&#39;s leader, Xi, near-term comfort, according to Craig Singleton, a senior fellow at Washington think tank Foundation for Defense of Democracies. But, he said, that is temporary: “With prominent Chinese theorists speculating that time may no longer be on Putin&#39;s side, Xi must now grapple with losing the very great-power clash he set in motion against the West.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Laurence Norman contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to James T. Areddy at <a href="mailto:James.Areddy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">James.Areddy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 16:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c<author><![CDATA[James T. Areddy]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>Aerospace/Defense</category><category> Defense Equipment/Products</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category> International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>risk news</category><category> military action</category><category> aerospace</category><category> defense</category><category> defense equipment</category><category>产品</category><category>industrial goods </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Movie-Theater Behavior Has Gone Off the Reels]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Theaters were once a no-phone zone. Now people are using devices without remorse. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101156"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="615" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827399?width=860&amp;height=615" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Some fans—though not these pictured—take out their phones and disturb moviegoers.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Iris Schneider/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101156"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-marie-alcantara"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-629922/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-marie-alcantara" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ann-Marie Alcántara</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 2, 2023 11:57 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/movie-theater-behavior-has-gone-off-the-reels-8d3ba0b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/barbie-oppenheimer-barbenheimer-premiere-e8007fe3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“Barbenheimer”</a> might be good for theaters, but it&#39;s bringing out some bad behavior in theatergoers.</p><p> Many attendees are forgetting the cardinal rule: Never take out a phone during the film. Instead, people are picking out selfies to post, scrolling during dull moments, even taking pictures of the screen—with the flash on. TikTok is inspiring a new generation of theatergoers to act out and even post their antics on social media.</p><p> The cinephiles sitting next to them have to decide whether to keep quiet or make an even bigger scene.</p><p> Vikash Patel goes to the movies most weeks in Savannah, Ga. The 27-year-old convenience-store owner watched “Barbie” and “Oppenheimer” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/barbenheimer-poised-to-deliver-blowout-weekend-at-the-box-office-9feef168?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">during opening weekend</a> . During his “Barbie” evening showing, someone took photos and videos during a Ken monologue. Patel didn&#39;t complain, but he says he heard several people in his row groan.</p><p> “There&#39;s a concert-ification of movies,” Patel says. “You want to experience the movie and share the experience at the same time.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827621?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Vikash Patel, sporting a Barbenheimer shirt, noticed someone taking smartphone photos and videos during the &#39;Barbie&#39; movie.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Vikash Patel</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Etiquette at public events has become harder to control and manage after the pandemic. At concerts, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/concertgoers-are-behaving-badly-blame-tiktok-11ce4737?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fans are rowdier than ever</a> , shrieking at artists, blocking people&#39;s views with signs, even throwing items at artists. At Broadway shows, <a href="https://twitter.com/ohalexsimmons/status/1646145215185448964" target="_blank" class="icon none">Playbill inserts</a> now remind people to turn off their phones and let the actors do the singing. And now, some movie venues are posting videos to <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@movielandcinemas/video/7121346935780330798?_r=1&amp;_t=8eLFcAYVwt9" target="_blank" class="icon none">teach people how to behave</a> .</p><p> “Barbie” and “Oppenheimer” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/movie-industry-really-needs-barbenheimer-to-stretch-its-legs-18cc1ba8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">continue to do well at the box office</a> , together grossing more than $1 billion in ticket sales globally. This creates a double-edged sword for theater operators: Hot movies put people back in the seats. But if a few attendees ruin the shared experience, more movie lovers might wait for the streaming version to come to their living rooms.</p><h3> Screens at screenings</h3><p> If you want to see clips from the hottest movies, just go to TikTok.</p><p> Sierra Moon, a 29-year-old book-publishing marketer in Philadelphia, pulled a Barbenheimer during opening weekend—and even saw “Barbie” a second time. Between showings, she came across scenes from both movies on TikTok. And during her “Barbie” screenings, she saw people taking photos and continuing to use their phones. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827625?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sierra Moon saw people use their phones during two different &#39;Barbie&#39; screenings.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Renee Miller</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “It&#39;s the first time I noticed that many people taking pictures of the screen during a movie,” Moon says. She imagines it will only get worse with coming flicks like the Timothée Chalamet-led “Wonka,” whose trailer already drove TikTokers into a small frenzy.</p><p> “There has been a big shift in how we act when we&#39;re in a movie theater and what the rules are these days,” Moon says.</p><p> Lexi Weigl, a 25-year-old operations coordinator at a marketing agency, watched “Barbie” without issue until about halfway through the movie. A few rows down, someone pulled out her phone. The woman scrolled through her notifications, then turned to her camera roll to decide which Barbie-outfit selfie to post on Instagram, says Weigl, who lives near Savannah, Ga.</p><p> Though Weigl was frustrated and angry, she tried to ignore it.</p><p> “I tried to just tune it out and focus on the movie because I&#39;m watching &#39;Barbie&#39; and I paid to be here,” she says. “But at the same time, it was like, &#39;Come on, this is so disrespectful.&#39;”</p><h3> Projecting politeness</h3><p> Alamo Drafthouse, a theater chain where patrons can order alcohol and food at their seats, has been calling out <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@alamodrafthouse/video/7145853015562390830" target="_blank" class="icon none">this kind of behavior on TikTok</a> over the past year. Last week, it tweeted a photo someone had taken with the flash on during “Oppenheimer,” asking guests to <a href="https://twitter.com/alamodrafthouse/status/1684669409267224576" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">not “even touch your phone</a> during the movie.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><amp-twitter width="486" height="657" layout="responsive" data-tweetid="1684669409267224576" data-cards="hidden"></amp-twitter></div><p> Alamo trains its staff to issue a one-time verbal warning to any guest who&#39;s disruptive at the movies, says Michael Kustermann, president and incoming chief executive of the company.</p><p> “We understand the level of enthusiasm,” Kustermann says. “Get there early and take a picture of the crowd while the lights are still on.”</p><p> Theater chains across the country are offering social-media photo ops in the lobbies, including giant Barbie boxes and other sets.</p><p> “The time to share the enthusiasm and excitement about that journey is after it ends,” says Michael O&#39;Leary, CEO of the National Association of Theatre Owners, a trade organization. “We always want to maintain the cinema as that special place where you shut out the distractions of everyday life and devote a couple of hours to a compelling story.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Have you witnessed any bad behavior at the movies lately? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><h3> Movie manners</h3><p> People got used to sitting at home during the pandemic, quickly posting photos of whatever they were watching on-screen.</p><p> “I feel like &#39;Barbie&#39; was ripe for it—being a movie that fans would feel comfortable or encouraged to do something like that,” says Chris Lambert, a 36-year-old who runs a movie explanation website and lives in the Austin, Texas, area. He watched “Barbie” twice during opening weekend and saw someone take out his phone to take photos of Margot Robbie, the movie&#39;s star, not once but twice. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827944?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Some theaters offer social-media photo ops in their lobbies, including giant Barbie boxes.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jenna Schoenefeld/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> But the behavior isn&#39;t welcome when others in the audience are trying to escape smartphones and enjoy a show.</p><p> “We&#39;re at a point where it&#39;s very easy for people to prioritize sharing something online at the expense of those around them,” he says.</p><p> At least now there&#39;s enough “Barbie” and “Oppenheimer” footage online, nobody needs to film any more. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F73F494F-CBD6-4993-950C-84DD6C248F61&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmovie-theater-behavior-has-gone-off-the-reels-8d3ba0b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Movie fans flocked to theaters for the release of “Barbie” and “Oppenheimer,” with some seeing the films back-to-back. Hollywood is hoping the summer blockbuster odd couple can give a boost to the box office. Photo: Siemond Chan/The Wall Street Journal<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
